ins and influence. During the Cold War, Canada’s military, industrial, and political partnerships developed behind the scenes and without much public scrutiny. Silent Partners explores Canada’s history of leveraging military and defence expenditures to fund domestic industries, bolster employment, and support science and technology. Military and defence spending have affected Canada in myriad ways, from demography and geography, to political economy and international relations, in uneven patterns of prosperity and decline. The contributions in this volume explore the environmental impacts of military activities and munitions production, the ethical issues of human experimentation and military testing, and the economic and political implications of procurement and arms exports. Silent Partners is an illuminating examination of Canada’s military-industrial complex from a historical perspective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aMilitary researchzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aMilitary-industrial complexzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Military / Canada.2bisacsh1 aDavis, Brandon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarish, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFitzpatrick, Meghan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaas, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKercher, Asa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSouchen, Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSouchen, Alex, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWakelam, Randall, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWiseman, Matthew S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb